    <item>
      <title>Anagram Animator</title>
      <link>https://colourlessspearmint.github.io/blog/anagram/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 18 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://colourlessspearmint.github.io/blog/anagram/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;An &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anagram&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Anagram&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; is a word created by rearranging the letters of another word.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;For example, my full name, &amp;lsquo;Ethan Oliver Marks&amp;rsquo;, is an anagram for &amp;lsquo;Martin Kolver Shea&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;figure&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://colourlessspearmint.github.io/media/example_anagram.gif&#34; alt=&#34;Ethan Oliver Marks ↔ Martin Kolver Shea&#34; /&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I generated the above animation using &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1MqpogsUUTuzctVKgg8n8btD3WUuENPAK&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Anagram Animator&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, a Colab Notebook I wrote in a few hours.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;figure&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://colourlessspearmint.github.io/media/anagramcolab.webp&#34; alt=&#34;A screenshot of Anagram Animator in Colab&#34; /&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;usage&#34;&gt;Usage&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I made Anagram Animator because my friends were making anagrams of our names one day and I wanted to contribute by making visualizations. None of my friends are programmers, so I specifically designed the notebook to be as easy to use as possible.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Eliza</title>
      <link>https://colourlessspearmint.github.io/blog/eliza/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 17 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://colourlessspearmint.github.io/blog/eliza/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ELIZA&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;ELIZA&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; was the first computer chatbot. Think of it as the great-great-great-grandparent of ChatGPT.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;figure&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1200/1*l_OiRGmLi-8yCrdjg5bfig.png&#34; alt=&#34;An example conversation with ELIZA&#34; /&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;ELIZA&amp;rsquo;s source code was written by Joseph Weizenbaum in 1966 in the &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SLIP_%28programming_language%29&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;SLIP&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; programming language, which is a fork of &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MAD_%28programming_language%29&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;MAD&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;. My computer obviously doesn&amp;rsquo;t run a 66-year-old programming language written for the &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNIVAC_1100/2200_series#1107&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;UNIVAC 1107&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I still wanted to test ELIZA as part of my &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://colourlessspearmint.github.io/blog/earlyai&#34;&gt;research on early AI&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, so I was left no other choice but to re-implement ELIZA for modern computers in Python.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
